<h2>This website used two data sources to pull the data.</h2>
<h2>CSV</h2>
  <h3>1. Dog Breeds Dataset (dog_breeds.csv):</h3>
  <p>
  <b>Description:</b> This dataset provides information about different dog breeds, including their names, groups, sections, countries of origin, URLs, images, and PDF files. The reference came from this link: https://github.com/paiv/fci-breeds.
  </p>
  <p><b>Structure:</b> The dataset consists of columns like "id", "breed_name", "group", "section", "country", "url", "image", and "pdf".
  </p>
  <p><b>Required Database Table and Columns:</b>The "Breeds" table with columns like "id", "name", "group", "section", "country", "url", "image", and "pdf".
  </p>
  <br>
  <h2>Faker </h2>
  <h3>2.1 Faker Data for Owners and Dogs:</h3>
  <p>
  <b>Description:</b> Faker is used to generate synthetic data for owners and their dogs.
  <p>
  <b>Structure:</b> The Faker data includes attributes like owner's name, email, dog's name, age, and the associated breed and owner.
  </p>
  <p><b>Required Database Tables and Columns:</b> The "Owners" table with columns like "id", "name", and "email". Additionally, a "Dogs" table with columns like "id", "name", "age", "breed_id" (foreign key referencing Breeds table), and "owner_id" (foreign key referencing Owners table).
  </p><br>
  <h3>2.2. Faker Data for Vet Visits:</h3>
  <p>
  <b>Description:</b> Faker is also used to generate synthetic data for vet visits made by dogs.
  </p>
  <b>Structure: </b>The Faker data includes attributes like visit date, description, and the associated dog.
  <p>
  <b>Required Database Table and Columns:</b> The "VetVisits" table with columns like "id", "visit_date", "description", and "dog_id" (foreign key referencing Dogs table).
  </p><br>
